name: Rust Treatment
shortDescription: Grind, Hammerite Kurust rust treatment, and white Rustoleum paint inside of van.
longDescription: Grind, Hammerite Kurust rust treatment, and white Rustoleum paint inside of van.
tools: Electric drill, metal grinding heads, foam paintbrushes

name: Negative Battery Wire Replaced
shortDescription: Replaced the main negative battery wire from the side-post battery.
longDescription: Remove the black/negative battery wire from the side-post battery. Disconnect the secondary ground wire by removing the bolt holding the terminal to the frame. Remove any brackets, zip ties, or wire runs/coverings. Remove the bolt holding the wire to the engine ground. Inspect the new wire to ensure it is the same size, has same terminals, and is in good condition. Strip the end of the secondary ground on the new/replacement wire. Put a new terminal connector on the end of the secondary ground wire; crimp and solder. Install the new wire by repeating the above steps in reverse order.
tools: 5mm wrench, 1/2" socket and wrench, wire brush, wire stripper, pliers, soldering iron

name: Fuel Filter Replaced
longDescription: 13mm bolt on the holding bracket. 20mm bolt on the filter. 13mm bolt on the fuel line that tightens to the filter. Place an oil catch or bucket as fuel will drip when removing. Remove the out and in fuel line bolts. Loosen and slide off the bracket. Pull out the old filter; be prepared for gas to leak and spill. Compare parts to ensure they match. Make sure the fuel filter is replaced in the same orientation (OUT towards engine, IN comes from the gas tank). Check the O-rings on the in and out fuel line ends; replace if necessary. Slide the new filter in. Semi-tighten the in and out bolts. Position and tighten the hold bracket. Tighten all connections. When going to start the engine turn the key to on, then turn it off 2-3 times to prime the pump and put gas in the lines and filter. After the third time start the engine then immediately look at the new fuel filter to ensure there are no leaks.

name: Brake Check
shortDescription: check water ratio in brake oil

name: Transmission Fluid and Filter Changed
shortDescription: Removed the transmission pan and replaced the fluid and filter.
longDescription: 16 bolt transmission pan 1/2" socketing wrench. To access I had to remove the transmission mount as it covered the bolts. After removing all bolts, drain the fluid into a catch container. Once drained remove the filter and inspect. Compare the new replacement filter with the old to ensure they are the same size and shape. Ensure the filter gasket isn't stuck up in the transmission so you don't have two gaskets. Lube the gasket with some transmission oil. Install the filter. Install the pan, don't over tighten the bolts. Measure how much oil you removed and replace with new oil via the transmission dip stick tube. Half quart at a time as you get close, allow to settle and measure with the dip stick. Once the level looks close start the engine, warm up, and with foot on brake shift slowly through the gears to distribute the new oil. Do this a few times as you top off and measure the oil level. Do not overfill. Check level again over the next few trips/days.
